How can we make our minds around all these stats?

Confusion Matrix¶

The first thing we see is the so-called confusion matrix? This is nothing more than a hit matrix, where we can have a first glance on how the model Prediction relates to the Reference (i.e. actual realization).

Ideally, we would like to see higher values on the main diagonal of the Confusion Matrix, and lower value elsewhere. This would hints to the fact that the model tends to correctly predict the classes.

True Positive¶

Taken one class as reference, (in a bivariate settings it is usually the target of our test), we define a true positive an observation belonging to the target class (i.e. the positive class), which has been correctly predicted .

Here below, if we consider class Yes (survived status), as our reference class, we can see that we have 94 true positive predictions.

In [4]:
acc$table

          Reference
Prediction Not Yes
       Not 218  37
       Yes  43  94

True Negative¶

Conversely, taken one class as reference, (in a bivariate settings it is usually the target of our test), we define a true negative an observation not belonging to the target class (i.e. any other negative class), which has been correctly predicted .

Here below, if we consider class Yes (survived status), as our reference class, we can see that we have 218 true negative predictions (that is, class Not has been correctly predicted 218 times).

In [5]:
acc$table

          Reference
Prediction Not Yes
       Not 218  37
       Yes  43  94

False Positive¶

Let's start talking about errors. We have a false positive everytime our model thinks an observation belongs to the target class (i.e. the positive class), but it is actually wrong.

In the titanic example, if we consider class Yes as our reference class, we can see that we have 43 false positive predictions.

In [6]:
acc$table

          Reference
Prediction Not Yes
       Not 218  37
       Yes  43  94

False Negative¶

Likewise, a false negative, is any observation that actually belongs to the reference class (i.e. it does not belongs to any negative class), but it is classified as such.

Again, in our example we have 37 false negative.

In [7]:
acc$table

          Reference
Prediction Not Yes
       Not 218  37
       Yes  43  94

More than two classes¶

As you can see. the concept of confusion matrix is easily extensible to a multivariate setting.

IF GD7 is our reference class:

  • how many true positive? 136
  • how many true negative? 995
  • how many false positive? 7
  • how many false negative? 4

Also, keep in mind that:

  • $P = TP + FN$
  • $N = TN + FP$

Accuracy¶

From the definition of true/false positive/negative, we can mutuate the accuracy metric, defined as $ \frac{TP+TN}{P+N}$. I would rather call this metric how many correct guesses?

In the Titanic example our model achieves an out-of-sample accuracy of circa: $79\% = \frac{94 + 218}{94 + 218 + 43 + 37}$

In [8]:
acc$table

acc$overall[1] %>% round(2)

          Reference
Prediction Not Yes
       Not 218  37
       Yes  43  94
Accuracy: 0.8

Precision¶

Another relevant statistic is the precision, which is the ability of the model to detect properly the target (i.e. positive class), which is defined as $\frac{TP}{TP + FP}$

In the Titanic example our model has a precision of almost $69\% = \frac{94}{94+43}$

Accuracy Paradox¶

Up to now, we have been looking at the performance of the model overall. But we previously assumed Rose was interested only to the following profile:

  • male
  • legal age
  • not too old

So, we would be better of examining the performance of our model on that specific subset of interest. Let's do it!

In [9]:

Ok, 81%. At a first glance, it looks like we have even better performances on this small sample. Let's plot something out.

In [10]:
test_response_probabilities_df = model %>%
  predict(newdata = titanic_df_filtered$x_test,
          type = 'prob') %>% pull('Yes') %>% data_frame('Probabilities' = .)

# the following is a quite articulated piece of code to plot the interactive graph
# it is ggplot based, nothing too much complicated. Feel free to ask if not clear

df = data_frame()
df_tmp = data_frame()

for(threshold in seq(max(min(test_response_probabilities_df$Probabilities) - 0.01,0),
                     max(test_response_probabilities_df$Probabilities) + 0.01,
                     by = 0.01)){
  
  
  test_response_df = test_response_probabilities_df %>%
    mutate(Response = if_else(Probabilities > threshold, 1, 0) %>% factor(., levels = 0:1))
  
  df_tmp = bind_cols(test_response_df %>% mutate(Response = factor(Response, levels = 0:1)),
                     titanic_df_filtered$y_test$class %>% data_frame('survived' = .) %>%  mutate(survived = factor(survived, labels = 0:1))) %>% 
    mutate(Threshold = threshold,
           Accuracy = confusionMatrix(Response, survived, positive = '1')[['overall']]['Accuracy'],
           Sensitivity = confusionMatrix(Response, survived, positive = '1')[['byClass']]['Sensitivity'],
           Specificity = confusionMatrix(Response, survived, positive = '1')[['byClass']]['Specificity'],
           Precision = confusionMatrix(Response, survived, positive = '1')[['byClass']]['Precision'],
           Recall = confusionMatrix(Response, survived, positive = '1')[['byClass']]['Recall'],
           Balanced = confusionMatrix(Response, survived, positive = '1')[['byClass']]['Balanced Accuracy'],
           ROC = roc(Response, survived) %>% auc
          )
  
  df = bind_rows(df, df_tmp)
  
  
}


p = ggplot(df) +
  geom_line(aes(x = Probabilities, y = Accuracy, frame = Threshold, label = Accuracy)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("red", "blue")) +
  theme_minimal() + ggtitle('Titanic Model | Response Plot') +
  geom_point(aes(x = Probabilities, y = as.numeric(Response) - 1, color = survived, frame = Threshold)) +
  theme(legend.position="none")

Let's introduce a new hyperparameter, that we will call classification treshold which discriminates on the propability space which observations are classified in either classes.

The default classification treshold is set to classify every observation with a model probability probability greater than 0.5 as a survivor, and vice versa

In [11]:
ggplotly(p, height = 500, width = 500)

Indeed, if we set the classification threshold to 0.5, we obtain the accuracy we would expect. (81%)

But how is it possible that if we raise the treshold to its maximum we get the highest (86%) accuracy? This does not make sense!! This is clearly not the best model!

Think about it: it is like we were saying: "everybody's gonna die anyway, don't choose anyone!".

If Nostradamus was enough, we would have needed no machine learning!

...ok maybe the accuracy metric is simply not the most suited metric to appraise model performance. According to the confusion matrix, only two istances from the positive class are classified correctly, 11 are instead misclassified.

Let's introduce some concept to better understand the concept.

Prevalence¶

Prevalence is an indicator of class unbalance. In our setting, only 15% of istances belong to the positive class.

Defined as $\frac{P}{P+N}$

In [13]:
acc_paradox[['byClass']]['Prevalence'] %>% round(2)
Prevalence: 0.15

No Information Rate¶

Indeed, prior drawing conclusion regarding the goodness of the model, we should check how much the data is biased. The No Information Rate could be defined as the accuracy of a stupid classifier (e.g. our Nostradamus classifier).

In [14]:
acc_paradox[['overall']]['AccuracyNull'] %>% round(2)
AccuracyNull: 0.85

Sensitivity¶

Sometimes also referred to as sensibility, recall, hit rate or true positive rate, the sensitivity metric tells how good is the model in discriminating the reference class (i.e. positive class).

  • In other words: how good is the model in correctly identifying a positive as positive?

It is defined as $\frac{TP}{P}$.

Type II error¶

Is defined as 1-sensitivity.

In [15]:
acc_paradox$table

acc_paradox[['byClass']]['Sensitivity']  %>% round(2)

          Reference
Prediction Not Yes
       Not  99  16
       Yes   7   2
Sensitivity: 0.11

Specificity¶

Alias true negative rate - opposite to sensitivity - he specificity metrics tells how good is the model in discriminating istance not in the reference class (i.e. negative class)

  • In other words, how good is the model in correctly identifying istances not belonging to the reference class?

It is defined as $\frac{TN}{N}$

Type I Error¶

Defined as 1-specificity

In [16]:

acc_paradox[['byClass']]['Specificity']  %>% round(2)

          Reference

Indeed, discriminating between classes can be crucial...

Type I Type II error. What's more relevant?¶

depending on the problem, type I or type II error may be more relevant, but in general, there is a good trade off between the two

  • in spam identification, i am better off with a high specificity, because I do not want to identify useful mail as spam
  • in disease diagnostic, i do am better off with a high specificity, because I do not want to prescribe medicine if they are not needed.
    • you do not want to go through chemio unless strictly necessary
    • however sometimes, e.g. if you are a blood donor, you absolutely do not want to use the ematic component of a donor which is not suited to donated.
      • this is why test needs to be extremely sensitive. this comes at a cost of reducing specificity, as i am more likely to identify a false positive. You want to be very sure not to receive blood from someone with the syphilis

Recap¶

Back to a multiclass setting¶

Again, you can extend the concept of sensitivity and specificity to a multivariate problem.

Defined a reference class, you treat that as positive, all the othes as a larger, unique, negative class.

A big question.¶

  • Is there a way to have an indicator agnostic to the effect of prevalence?

   - Yes
Actually, there's a few

Kohen's Kappa¶

$$\frac{\text{Accuracy - No Information Rate}}{1 - \text{No Information Rate}}$$

In [18]:
acc_paradox$table

acc_paradox[['overall']]['Kappa'] %>% round(2)

          Reference
Prediction Not Yes
       Not  99  16
       Yes   7   2
Kappa: 0.06

Balanced Accuracy¶

$$ (\text{Sensitivity + Specificity})* \frac{1}{2} $$

In [19]:
acc_paradox[['byClass']]['Balanced Accuracy'] %>% round(2)
Balanced Accuracy: 0.52

Receiver Operating Characteristics¶

Graphically shows the trade off between sensitivity and specificity

Historical note¶

The ROC curve was first used during World War II for the analysis of radar signals before it was employed in signal detection theory. Following the attack on Pearl Harbor in 1941, the United States army began new research to increase the prediction of correctly detected Japanese aircraft from their radar signals. For this purposes they measured the ability of radar receiver operators to make these important distinctions, which was called the Receiver Operating Characteristics.

test_response_probabilities = model %>%
  predict(newdata = titanic_df$x_test,
         type = 'prob') %>% pull('Yes')

p = roc(test_response_probabilities, titanic_df$y_test$class %>% factor(labels = 0:1))[2:3] %>%
    as.data.frame.list %>%
    as_data_frame %>%
    mutate(slider = fpr %>% round(2)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = fpr, y = tpr)) + geom_line() + ggtitle('ROC Curve') +
    xlab('False Positive Ratio (1 - Specificity)') + 
    ylab('True Positive Ratio (Sensitivity)') +
    geom_point(aes(x=fpr, y = tpr, frame = slider)) +
    theme_minimal()

p = p %>% animation_opts(frame = 10, easing = 'cubic-in-out', mode = 'afterall')

ggplotly(p, height = 500, width = 450)

The best model is the one that better manages the trade off between sensitivity and specificity

  • that is to say, the more skewed the curve towards the top left corner, the better

Accuracy Ratio (Gini Index)¶

The AUC value can be misleading in that, depite taking values between 0 and 1, the baseline classifier (i.e. the coin toss discriminator) has a AUC of 0.5. To solve this problem, we normalize the AUC metrics by the following transormation.

$ \text{AR} = 2 \cdot (\text{AUC}) - 1$

In this way, the random discriminator has an Accuracy Ratio equal to zero.

In [23]:
roc(test_response_probabilities,titanic_df$y_test$class %>%
    factor(labels = 0:1)) %>%
    auc(.) %>%
    round(2)*2-1 %>% 
    list('AR' = .) %>% unlist
AR: 0.7

Aaand.. back to multivariate¶

  • when sample are unbalanced

    1. Volume under surface.

      • No interpretation
      • $O(n^2)$

    2. weighted AUROC.

      • toxic comment classification challenge

  • when sample unbalance is less important

    1. accuracy is totally fine (in mnist the sample is e.g. perfectly balanced)

  • others

    • object segmentation: IoU (intersection over union)

      • which pixels belongs to a certain object?
